     <section name="Description">

  <p>The <a href="http://www.jbundle.org">jbundle.org</a> <strong>Auto Web Start</strong> program lets you easily launch
  your java client applications from a web browser.</p>

<p>
Just install your java jars in your web server, provide the main class name and <b>Auto Web Start</b> will figure out the rest.
</p>
<p>
Here's how it works:<br/>
When you install your jars in your web server an OSGi manifest is automatically added to your jars. This
tells the server what packages the jar contains and what external packages are required to run.
When you are ready to run your application or applet from a web browser, <b>Auto Web Start</b> converts these
dependencies to a web start jnlp file. It also, does a pack200/gzip compression that can reduce the download
size of your files by an order of magnitude.
</p>
<p>
All you have to do is specify the main java class in your url. For example, to run a program in a web page:<br/>
<code>
<a href="/webstart/applet.html?applet=org.jbundle.util.biorhythm.Biorhythm">http://www.jbundle.org/webstart/applet.html?applet=org.jbundle.util.biorhythm.Biorhythm</a><br/>
</code>
To run this program as a stand-alone application:<br/>
<code>
<a href="/webstart/biorhythm?mainClass=org.jbundle.util.biorhythm.Biorhythm">http://www.jbundle.org/webstart/biorhythm?mainClass=org.jbundle.util.biorhythm.Biorhythm</a><br/>
</code>
<strong>Auto Web Start</strong> takes care of all the Web Start configuration. It even automatically
updates the jnlp and java jar files when you update your application.
</p>

